📅 Post 1: The Core Concept & Core Architecture
Goal: Demystify what an API is and explain the relationship between a user interface and business logic using the Uber analogy.

Headline: What actually happens under the hood when you request an Uber? 🚗

To a user, booking a ride looks like a simple button tap. But beneath that sleek interface, your action triggers a complex network of backend systems talking via APIs (Application Programming Interfaces).

Most modern software follows a strict Frontend/Backend architecture:

💻 The Frontend (GUI): The visual interface built for everyday users. It captures your actions (like entering an address) and turns them into a structured request.

⚙️ The Backend: The heavy-lifting engine running on servers. It contains dedicated APIs that handle the real logic independently:

Mapping API: Locates your exact coordinates.

Matching Algorithm API: Finds the nearest available drivers.

Fare Engine API: Calculates prices dynamically based on traffic and demand.

Payment API: Securely talks to banking networks to process receipts.

Why this matters for engineering: By separating the system into independent API layers, backend engineers can optimize ride-matching algorithms or update databases without ever breaking the mobile app users have on their phones.

Decoupling systems early is step one to building scalable software!

