📅 Post 2: API Scopes (Public vs. Private vs. Code Libraries)
Goal: Prove you understand that APIs exist at different layers of infrastructure, from public data-sharing to internal microservices and code libraries.

Headline: Not all APIs are built the same way. Here are the 3 layers developers use daily 📊

When people talk about APIs, they usually think about fetching weather data or processing credit cards. But in system design, APIs are classified by who uses them and where they live.

Here is a quick breakdown of the three types:

🌐 1. Open / Public APIs
Built for external developers. Companies expose these to let third-party apps integrate with their platform. For example, using the YouTube Search API to pull video thumbnails and descriptions directly into a custom learning dashboard.

🔒 2. Internal / Private APIs
Built strictly for communication within a single organization. Think of Amazon: when you check out, independent microservices (Inventory, Logistics, Billing) talk to each other securely behind the scenes using internal APIs to update stock and process shipping.

🛠️ 3. Code Interfaces (Library APIs)
These don't travel over the internet at all. They are pre-defined, high-level functions built into programming languages or frameworks to save time. Think of Python's .sort() method or TensorFlow's deep learning layers. They abstract away complex math so you don't have to reinvent the wheel.

The Takeaway: Great system architecture relies on placing the right boundaries around these layers to ensure both security and reusability.

