📅 Post 3: System Architecture (REST vs. GraphQL vs. gRPC vs. SOAP)
Goal: Show hiring teams you understand deep system design trade-offs and communication protocols.

Headline: REST vs. GraphQL vs. gRPC vs. SOAP: How do engineers choose? 🤔

APIs communicate using different architectural styles and protocols. In system design, choosing the right protocol isn't about finding the "best" one—it's about understanding the architectural trade-offs.

Here is how the big four compare:

🔹 REST: The global standard. It relies on standard HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) and works with stateless, resource-oriented URLs. It's incredibly reliable for standard web and mobile applications.

🔹 GraphQL: The client's best friend. Instead of hitting multiple endpoints, the client sends a single custom query specifying exactly the fields it needs. This completely eliminates over-fetching data over slow mobile networks.

🔹 gRPC: The internal speed demon. Developed by Google, it transmits compressed binary data (Protocol Buffers) over HTTP/2 instead of heavy text blocks. Perfect for low-latency microservice-to-microservice communication.

🏛️ SOAP: The enterprise veteran. An older, highly structured protocol based strictly on XML messaging. It’s heavy, but its strict security compliance rules keep it alive in banking and healthcare.

💡 Trade-off Insight: A scalable modern app might use REST or GraphQL for public endpoints to remain developer-friendly, while utilizing gRPC internally to keep backend latency minimal.

