📅 Post 4: The Developer Workflow (Documentation, Authentication & Postman)
Goal: Transition from theory to practical engineering habits. Shows you know how to read docs, secure keys, and use testing tools like Postman or cURL.

Headline: The developer's blueprint for integrating a new API 🛠️

Shifting from writing isolated local code to fetching live data from third-party services is a major milestone for any developer. But before writing application code, a structured testing workflow saves hours of debugging.

Here is the exact checklist I follow to safely integrate a new endpoint:

📑 1. Deep-Dive the Documentation
Locate the base URL, endpoints, and required parameters. For example, a weather API needs the city parameter formatted perfectly (q=London) or it rejects the request.

🔑 2. Isolate and Protect Authentication
Most APIs require an API Key or Bearer Token. Treat these like production passwords. Never hardcode them directly into your client-side files or public GitHub repos—always utilize environment variables (.env).

🧪 3. Test Sandbox Requests First
Before writing any application logic, hit the endpoint using Postman or run a raw terminal command:
curl -X GET "[https://api.example.com/data?appid=YOUR_KEY](https://api.example.com/data?appid=YOUR_KEY)"
If you get a clean 200 OK and a structured JSON payload here, you know your credentials and URLs are flawless.

💻 4. Implement the Code Interface
Once verified, bring the request into your codebase using modern HTTP clients like Axios or the native Fetch API.

