📅 Post 5: Defensive Coding (Error Handling & HTTP Status Codes)
Goal: Showcase production-ready thinking. This proves you write clean code that safely handles edge cases, server drops, and validation issues.

Headline: Writing production-ready APIs means coding for when things go completely wrong 🛑

Writing code for a successful API request is easy. But external networks are unpredictable: users input typos, API tokens expire unexpectedly, and third-party servers drop offline.

Production-ready backend development is defined by defensive error handling. Your code must catch failures early and communicate clearly using structured HTTP status codes:

🔍 400 Bad Request / 404 Not Found
If a client sends an unvalidated input (like a non-existent ID), your backend must intercept it early, stop execution, and return an explicit error string so the frontend UI can display a helpful message to the user.

🔑 401 Unauthorized
When authorization tokens expire or refresh cycles fail, your logic must explicitly handle the exception to trigger a clean login or re-authentication flow rather than allowing the application server to crash.

⏳ 429 Too Many Requests (Rate Limits)
Popular public APIs restrict high-volume access to prevent abuse. Implementing rate-limiting catches and retry logic ensures your application respects provider constraints gracefully.

Code Takeaway: Happy-path code gets an application running; robust exception handling keeps it alive in production.

